Exercise 2

First lets plot the data in the dino dataset:

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")
ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

And next calculate the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

For this example, instead of using dino_data youre going to change the dataset to star_data. Note that the R chunks are labeled with plot-star and cor-star to provide spaces to place the code for plotting and calculating the correlation coefficient. If done right, a graph of a star should pop up.

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "star")
ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Now to calculate the correlation coefficient. Youre going to pipe (%>%) your data set and then summarize the correlation between x and y.

star_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

As you can see, the value is bigger in the star_data than the value in the dino_data. about -0.0630 (star_data) > about -0.0645 (dino_data)

Exercise 4

For this exercise, were going to plot a circle dataset. Youre going to assign datasaurus_dozen to circle_data. Then filter and set dataset == cirlcle. Now use ggplot to visualize the data. Type which data to use and define the aesthetic mapping using x = x and y = y. To end this code, youre going to type geom_point to define the geometric shapes.

Before setting plotting the dataset, label your section. For this section, youre going to set it up as r plot-circle.

circle_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "circle")
ggplot(data = circle_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Now to measuer the correleation coefficent of the circle dataset. Pipe the dataset and summarize in r correlating x and y.

circle_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0683

This results in the value being smaller than the r of dino. The correlation coeffiecient of this dataset is -0.0683 and the r of the dino dataset is -0.0645

Exercise 5

For this exercise, were going to plot all the datasets together. First, youre going to add R chucks and label as plot-all. Then write down the code to plot.

ggplot(datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset))+
geom_point()+
facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) + #facet the dataset variable, in 3 cols

Youre going to create another chunk here again and label it as cor-all. For this section, youre going to calculate the correlation coefficient of all the graphs.

datasaurus_dozen %>%
